WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:06.320
&gt;&gt; Announcer: From the Library
of Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:07.690
&gt;&gt; Eleanor Billington: I'm
so honored to be here today

00:00:07.690 --> 00:00:11.680 position:56%
to introduce Luis Alberto Urrea, a
member of the Latino Literature Hall

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.130
of Fame and author of 16 books
include fiction, non-fiction,

00:00:15.130 --> 00:00:16.740
short stories, and poetry.

00:00:16.740 --> 00:00:20.890
Luis is a master storyteller who
moves effortlessly between genres.

00:00:20.890 --> 00:00:22.630
He is perhaps best
known for his writing

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:26.150
about the U.S.-Mexican border born
in Tijuana to a Mexican father

00:00:26.150 --> 00:00:28.740
and an American mother, Luis
understands the complexity

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:30.570
of border life and
the inherent tension

00:00:30.570 --> 00:00:32.460
in living between two worlds.

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:35.160
His memoir, "Nobody's Son,
Notes from an American Life,"

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:37.600
won the 1999 American Book Award

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.170
and chronicles his early
childhood growing up in Tijuana

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:42.600
and his family's immigration
to the United States.

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:45.800
Published in 2004, "The
Devil's Highway," a harrowing,

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:48.120
non-fiction account of
Mexican immigrants lost

00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:51.560
in the Arizona desert was a
finalist for the Pulitzer Prize.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:54.600
His 2005 historical novel,
"The Hummingbird's Daughter,"

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:56.470
tells the story of his
great aunt Teresa Urrea,

00:00:56.470 --> 00:00:59.630
and involved 20 years
of research and writing.

00:00:59.630 --> 00:01:02.220 position:56%
Along with "The Devil's Highway," it
was named the best book of the year

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:05.900
by many publications and won the
[inaudible] Prize in Fiction.

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:08.810
His most recent title, "The
Water Museum," is a finalist

00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:11.560
for the Pen Faulkner Award and was
named the best book of the year

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:15.540
by The Washington Post and
Kirkus Reviews among many others.

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:18.410
Like much of Lisa's work,
these short stories,

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:21.680
these 13 short stories reflect
a sensitivity and allegiance

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:23.970
to both sides of his
family's heritage.

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:25.640
The collection exhibits
an impressive range

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:27.670
of style and subject matter.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:30.680
From "Welcome to the Water
Museum," a dystopian tale of life

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:33.630
in the future where children
consider water an anomaly.

00:01:33.630 --> 00:01:37.030
To "Carnations and the White Girl,"
"Vignettes of Grief of Loneliness,"

00:01:37.030 --> 00:01:39.970
to the Edgar Award winning
"Amapola," which tells the story

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:43.390
of a teen romance with a very
dark twist to the comedic,

00:01:43.390 --> 00:01:47.180 position:56%
"Tape to the Sky," a look at an East
coast's academic's haphazard efforts

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:50.110
to reconcile with his
wife's infidelity.

00:01:50.110 --> 00:01:53.250
The stories in "The Water
Museum" largely depict outsiders.

00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:56.330
Individual displaced by
geography and poverty but also

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:58.450
by their grief and their longing.

00:01:58.450 --> 00:02:01.110
While not every story is linked
in the collection, each one builds

00:02:01.110 --> 00:02:03.400
on the previous, creating
a community of character

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:05.100
that is exquisitely drawn.

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:06.590
Their collective voice is haunting.

00:02:06.590 --> 00:02:09.420
It reflects a desire for
connection despite societal

00:02:09.420 --> 00:02:11.070
and cultural divides.

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:14.170
It is these moments of connection
between characters however brief

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:16.370
or imperfect that shine brightest

00:02:16.370 --> 00:02:20.460
and convey Luis's self-proclaimed
interest in bridges not borders.

00:02:20.460 --> 00:02:22.420
For the past three years,
we've had the pleasure

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:24.210
of working directly with Luis.

00:02:24.210 --> 00:02:27.640
His book "Into the Beautiful
North" is part of the NEA Big Read,

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:30.390
