and stinkier, and he pulled

00:14:01.060 --> 00:14:04.040
out a cigarette lighter he
had stolen from his mom.

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:05.340
And he lit it.

00:14:05.340 --> 00:14:09.330
And it was a dead pig
full of maggots.

00:14:09.330 --> 00:14:13.880
And we were just like ahh
looking at this thing.

00:14:13.880 --> 00:14:15.180
And I still remember him.

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:17.790
He looked at us and he
goes, "Ain't nothing.

00:14:17.790 --> 00:14:20.310
It's death.

00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:22.790
Death don't got nothing
to do with us."

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:27.840
And we walked out to
the light [laughter].

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:32.850
You know? You got to write.

00:14:32.850 --> 00:14:35.100
And I want to just
put this as an aside.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:38.750
And since we are in DC and
this is an election year,

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:46.630
I just want to say Ugo
Milan, if you ever watch TV,

00:14:46.630 --> 00:14:49.130
you know the The Dog
Whisperer, right?

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:50.490
Cesar Milan.

00:14:50.490 --> 00:14:51.790
Get out of here.

00:14:51.790 --> 00:14:53.270
That's not Cesar Milan.

00:14:53.270 --> 00:14:57.370
His name is Cesar Milan.

00:14:57.370 --> 00:15:00.290
He is a cousin of my cousins.

00:15:00.290 --> 00:15:02.310
He is from [inaudible].

00:15:02.310 --> 00:15:14.220 position:56%
And I just want to say, the man came
to the United States undocumented.

00:15:14.220 --> 00:15:16.750
He did. No papers.

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.790
His only skill was
talking to dogs [laughter].

00:15:19.790 --> 00:15:27.710
And now he is a millionaire
media star.

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:29.010
All right?

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:31.120
So, America, I don't
care what you hear

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:35.250
about America not working,
still works.

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:37.050
Still works.

00:15:37.050 --> 00:15:42.060
[ Applause ]

00:15:42.060 --> 00:15:44.600
So, just briefly I just, you know,
want to give you a little more

00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:46.100
about this writing thing.

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:47.490
Two things.

00:15:47.490 --> 00:15:50.370
One was his mother.

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:57.010
Ugo Milan's mother was
named Tia Flaca [phonetic],

00:15:57.010 --> 00:15:59.850
which means Aunt Skinny.

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:02.820
Tia Flaca was in fact skinny.

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:04.400
Lifelong diabetic.

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:06.260
Everybody in my family.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:08.600
I think everybody in
Mexico, diabetic.

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:11.570
And I grew up watching her
getting her shots every day.

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:13.490
They gave them to her in her leg.

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:15.850
In her thigh.

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:19.040
And picture this woman.

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:21.700
She was stylish in her own way.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:25.570
She wore cat eye glasses.

00:16:25.570 --> 00:16:26.870
Remember those?

00:16:26.870 --> 00:16:29.160
With glitter in them.

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:34.380
And being diabetic she had
gone blind in her left eye.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:38.430
And so it was always a
little squinchy [phonetic].

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:43.830
And she always smoked menthol
cigarettes around the clock

00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:46.140
but always clamped
them on the left side.

00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:47.440
So, there was always smoke.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:49.400
It looked like it was
coming out of her bad eye.

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:53.030
There was smoke coming out.

00:16:53.030 --> 00:16:55.850
And she controlled us with stories.

00:16:55.850 --> 00:16:58.950
She lied in other words to
make us do what she wanted.

00:16:58.950 --> 00:17:02.810
For example, she hated
a mess in the house.

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:05.290
She did not, she figured, you
know, I'm a working woman.

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:08.500
I don't have time to clean the
house, so don't make a mess.

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:11.430
She used to go every morning
to a tuna cannery to work

00:17:11.430 --> 00:17:13.910
in San Diego and come
back exhausted.

00:17:13.910 --> 00:17:15.510
She was not going to clean house.

00:17:15.510 --> 00:17:18.360
Now, my grandmother,
her mom, and by the way,

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:21.810
if you're asking yourself why
does this dude look Irish,

00:17:21.810 --> 00:17:24.020
I will tell you because
my grandmother

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:28.610
from [inaudible] was named
Guadalupe Murray [phonetic].

00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:33.870
So, red haired, blue-eyed
Irish Mexican lass.

00:17:33.870 --> 00:17:37.810
So, we called her Mama Lupita.

00:17:37.810 --> 00:17:40.450
Mama Lupita was a lapsed Catholic.

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:42.950 position:56%
She didn't want to deal with church.

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:44.250
Mass. Get out of here.

00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:45.720
You know, she had better
things to do.

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:51.060
So, she would every Friday fry
a fish for the young priest.

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:53.640
And he'd walk down from
the church and eat his fish

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:55.390
and get out of our house.

00:17:55.390 --> 00:17:58.300
And she got these ideas that
you could do symbolic things

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:03.130
that God liked like burn incense.

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:04.430
She thought, "Yeah.

00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:05.880
Yeah. God likes incense.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:08.870
So, I'll burn some
incense and he will see,

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:10.440
you know, house is full of smoke."

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:14.150
And then she realized he could
count the cones of incense.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:16.550
So, she would do like
20 cones a day.

00:18:16.550 --> 00:18:21.260
Right? But it never occurred to her
to actually put them in saucers.

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:24.590
So, she put the cones on
window ledges and on the piano.

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:27.450
So there were burns
everywhere and stains

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:29.350
of the resin all over the house.

00:18:29.350 --> 00:18:35.070
But she also did not like to
get rid of the cone of ash.

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:37.530
I think she was figuring God
is going to keep a tally.

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:41.070
You know God has a little
check that says, "Ah ha.

00:18:41.070 --> 00:18:43.470
Lupita did 27.

00:18:43.470 --> 00:18:44.770
That's good.

00:18:44.770 --> 00:18:46.070
It erases a couple of sins."

00:18:46.070 --> 00:18:47.900
Right? "Oh, she was
down to 15 today."

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:49.840
Well, you know?

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:54.480
So, the house was full of
cones of ash from the incense.

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:57.880
And I didn't know what they were.

00:18:57.880 --> 00:19:01.600
I saw them and I was thinking,
"That is really weird.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:03.110
What is that stuff?"

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:05.200
And remember, Tia Flaca
didn't want a mess.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:08.230
She didn't want to be
sweeping up ashes, right?

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:09.530
So, I stupidly went to her.

00:19:09.530 --> 00:19:11.990
I said, "Tia, [foreign
language spoken] Tia.

00:19:11.990 --> 00:19:18.680
All those cones every place?"

00:19:18.680 --> 00:19:22.130
And she said, "Oh."

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:23.430
She got very serious.

00:19:23.430 --> 00:19:24.730
"[inaudible].

00:19:24.730 --> 00:19:33.200
Those are the souls of
dead men [laughter]."

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:36.740 position:56%
She said, "If you break them, the
house is going to fill with spirits.

00:19:36.740 --> 00:19:38.130
Don't touch."

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:39.430
So, there was no mess [laughter].

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:43.550
And the other little
thing, which is truly one

00:19:43.550 --> 00:19:49.450
of the I think deepest inspirations
for writing in my life was this.

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:54.030
She didn't like me
going out on the street.

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:55.890
It was rough.

00:19:55.890 --> 00:19:57.320
People shooting each other.

00:19:57.320 --> 00:19:59.580
Cars. Who knows what.

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:02.460
Dogs [inaudible].

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:05.180
So, my dad and my mom would leave.

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:07.580 position:56%
My mom worked in a department store.

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:09.540
He also worked in the tuna cannery.

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:15.220 position:56%
And Tia Flaca would leave later in
her '56 Chevy driving across, right?

00:20:15.220 --> 00:20:16.800
And there was I.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:19.500
And she would tell me,
"Meijo, I don't want you

00:20:19.500 --> 00:20:21.580
to go in the street today.

00:20:21.580 --> 00:20:22.880
Stay inside."

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:24.180
They had a phrase [foreign
language spoken].

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:28.400 position:56%
It was like, you know, you're a
street dog, which I thought was kind

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:32.990
of bad ass frankly, but,
and I would be all repentant

00:20:32.990 --> 00:20:34.290
like I had been with the nuns.

00:20:34.290 --> 00:20:35.620
"No, Tia. I won't go.

00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:36.920
I promise."

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:38.220
She says, "You promise me."

00:20:38.220 --> 00:20:39.520
"No, I promise.

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:43.330
I swear. I'm going to stay and
watch like Jeopardy with grandma.

00:20:43.330 --> 00:20:44.630
OK? It's OK."

00:20:44.630 --> 00:20:45.930
And so she'd go to work.

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:48.940
And as soon as she was
gone, out in the street

00:20:48.940 --> 00:20:50.810
because my little pals
were out there.

00:20:50.810 --> 00:20:52.650
We would play marbles.

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:53.950
[inaudible] we'd call them.

00:20:53.950 --> 00:20:57.390
Right? And you could get, you
could get a kite for a penny.

00:20:57.390 --> 00:20:58.770
So, we're flying kites.

00:20:58.770 --> 00:21:03.590
And you could buy candies, like
five, six candies for a penny.

00:21:03.590 --> 00:21:04.890
We were in heaven.

00:21:04.890 --> 00:21:06.210
There were dogs out there.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.320
And we could try to spin tops but
you couldn't do it in the the dirt

00:21:09.320 --> 00:21:11.270
but we'd keep trying all day long.

00:21:11.270 --> 00:21:13.120
Just stupid stuff.

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:18.340
And I was out there with my
homies, shooting marbles, right?

00:21:18.340 --> 00:21:19.770
Not paying any attention.

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:21.990
And all of the sudden they
all jumped up and ran away.

00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:24.560
And I was like, "What the heck?"

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:25.860
You know? Where'd they go?

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:31.410
And I look up and here comes Flaca
driving home in her '56 Chevy.

00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:34.090
Smoke pouring out of her eye.

00:21:34.090 --> 00:21:36.730
I thought, "Oh, no."

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:39.990
Oh my god.

00:21:39.990 --> 00:21:42.780
You know, and you start
confessing your sins.

00:21:42.780 --> 00:21:45.250
"Jesus, I did lie to my
Tia, but, you know, come on.

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:46.550
Give me a break.

00:21:46.550 --> 00:21:48.310
You died for me."

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:52.540
And she pulls up and I
stand up and I'm ready.

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:57.330
The worst punishment, those of
you with Mexican or Latina moms

00:21:57.330 --> 00:21:58.930 position:56%
or aunts know what I'm going to say.

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:03.550
The worst punishment than the yard
stick is what we call the chankla

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:07.320
[phonetic], which is the old
lady gets out her slipper

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:10.880
and wails on you with it.

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:12.920
And the funny thing
about them when they do

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:14.710
that is they get very formal.

00:22:14.710 --> 00:22:17.960
So, you become thou.

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:21.760
And as they hit you,
they explain every point

00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:23.560
of their agenda [laughter].

00:22:23.560 --> 00:22:34.060
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:37.310
They get more and more obscene
while they're calling you thou.

00:22:37.310 --> 00:22:40.930
And you're like raining slippers.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:46.870
And then the most diabolical
thing is they all have this eye.

00:22:46.870 --> 00:22:49.100
They could pass for the NFL.

00:22:49.100 --> 00:22:51.470
Because they let you
go and you start to run

00:22:51.470 --> 00:22:54.680
and slosh [phonetic], bam.

00:22:54.680 --> 00:22:59.320
They always get you at the last
second on the back of the head.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:00.620
You know it's true.

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:03.470 position:56%
So, I was waiting for my punishment.

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:06.550
And I thought, "I'm going
to take it like a man."

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:08.190
My dad's big thing was "Be a man."

00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:10.660
So, I thought, OK, I'm
going to show him I'm a man.

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:11.960
And she got out of the car.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:13.260
And she took her cigarette.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:16.520
And she said, "Aye Luis.

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:19.790
Didn't I tell you to
stay out of the street?"

00:23:19.790 --> 00:23:21.270
I said, "Yes, Tia."

00:23:21.270 --> 00:23:23.350
"Didn't I tell you to stay inside?"

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:26.680
"Yes." "And what did you tell me?"

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:27.980
"That I would."

00:23:27.980 --> 00:23:29.280
"And what did you do?"

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:30.760
"I went outside."

00:23:30.760 --> 00:23:33.400
"And why did you go outside?"

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:36.150
"I don't know."

00:23:36.150 --> 00:23:40.040
And she said, "I don't care.

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:41.340
I give up.

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:42.640
I don't care.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:44.860
I can't control you anymore.

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:46.570
Do what you got to do, meijo.

00:23:46.570 --> 00:23:48.380
You want to be out on the street?

00:23:48.380 --> 00:23:49.680
Stay out on the street.

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:51.060
I've given up.

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:52.360
I'm going inside."

00:23:52.360 --> 00:23:53.770 position:56%
So, off she went with her cigarette.

00:23:53.770 --> 00:23:56.130
And I thought, "Oh, yes.

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:58.380
Thank you God.

00:23:58.380 --> 00:23:59.750
You love me."

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:01.640
And she got right to the door.

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:05.870
And she said, "Except there's
one thing I want to say to you."

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:08.000
And I said, "Yeah?"

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.100
And she came back.

00:24:10.100 --> 00:24:12.880
And she said, "Look around."

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:14.430
So, I looked around.

00:24:14.430 --> 00:24:16.580
"Look behind us."

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:18.250
I looked behind us.

00:24:18.250 --> 00:24:23.910
She said, "You see that Tijuana
has hills all around it?"

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:25.210
I said, "Yeah.

00:24:25.210 --> 00:24:29.300
Yeah." "There's mountains
even all around Tijuana."

00:24:29.300 --> 00:24:30.600
"Yeah, Tia."

00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:32.390
"Have you ever gone
up there, meijo?"

00:24:32.390 --> 00:24:34.940
Duh. "No."

00:24:34.940 --> 00:24:36.970
"Do you know what's up there?"

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:39.300
"No, Tia."

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:42.010
"Marijuana farms."

00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:43.310
I was like, "Really?"

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:44.610
"Oh, yeah."

00:24:44.610 --> 00:24:49.560
I thought, OK, you know, grown
ups are always saying weird stuff

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:50.860
to you.

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:52.160
I thought OK.

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.820
She said, "Do you know
how they grow marijuana?"

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:56.960
I said, "No, how do
they grow marijuana?"

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:09.640
"Oh, well, every afternoon around
now, the narcos send out trucks

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:13.440
with men with rifles in
the trucks and they drive

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:17.950
around Tijuana hunting for
little blonde boys playing

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:19.250
in the street [laughter].

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:22.740
And they use their guns.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:27.480
And they take those
little boys prisoner.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:30.150
And they take them to
the top of the mountain.

00:25:30.150 --> 00:25:34.410
And they force them to grow
marijuana at gunpoint."

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:36.920
And then she says, "But it's OK.

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:42.850
Stay out here if you
want to [laughter]."

00:25:42.850 --> 00:25:45.020
So, come on.

00:25:45.020 --> 00:25:47.920
I went inside.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:53.640
So, you know, I was deeply infected
with storytelling from the get go.

00:25:53.640 --> 00:25:55.820
And I truly loved it.

00:25:55.820 --> 00:25:59.880
And a little bit more of a
spiritual aspect that I just can't,

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:03.660
because it's not all fun and
games but there's a lot of beauty

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:05.930
in our roots and we
don't always know.

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:09.730
Sometimes, you know, we
think our roots are shameful.

00:26:09.730 --> 00:26:11.970
I'm not going to get political,

00:26:11.970 --> 00:26:15.490
but look at the Presidential
campaign this year.

00:26:15.490 --> 00:26:19.270
You know? And people tell
you that you're no good

00:26:19.270 --> 00:26:22.810
or your ancestors are no good
or you come from a neighborhood

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:26.600
with no hope and nothing but
terrible crime and murder.

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:29.900
You know, sometimes it's all
about the beauty of those places

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:32.300
that someone tells
you aren't beautiful.

00:26:32.300 --> 00:26:36.440
And for me Colonia
Independencia was beautiful, man.

00:26:36.440 --> 00:26:37.950
And the best part for me,

00:26:37.950 --> 00:26:42.530
I've talked about this
before, was the tortilla place.

00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:44.270
One of the times they
would let me go

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:47.180
out is they would give me some
money, and they'd say, "Luis,

00:26:47.180 --> 00:26:49.800
go buy a kilo of tortillas."

00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:51.500
Then I was cool, man,
because I'd walk

00:26:51.500 --> 00:26:54.000
up the hill toward
the tortilla place.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.960
And anybody who knows a
Mexican village or has old time

00:26:57.960 --> 00:26:59.810
because now they make
tortillas with machines.

00:26:59.810 --> 00:27:01.110
You don't get this anymore.

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:04.740
But from a certain distance
you hear the ladies doing this

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:06.040
[patting hands].

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:07.630
Right? It's like they're
applauding you.

00:27:07.630 --> 00:27:09.770
Yes. Yes [laughter].

00:27:09.770 --> 00:27:12.090
And it gets louder and
louder the closer you get.

00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:14.200
You start smelling the maize.

00:27:14.200 --> 00:27:15.670
And then you hear the radio.

00:27:15.670 --> 00:27:18.530
And then you hear them
laughing and talking.

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:20.280
And it's like entering to me,

00:27:20.280 --> 00:27:22.790
it was like entering this
weird state of grace.

00:27:22.790 --> 00:27:28.510
Like it's so magical it still
chokes me up to this day to think

00:27:28.510 --> 00:27:32.180
about being this little guy walking
up to the tortilla [inaudible]

00:27:32.180 --> 00:27:36.420
and stepping in this
rough, super hot room.

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:39.070
Four or six Mexican women,

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:43.710
many of them indigenous [patting
hands], making tortillas.

00:27:43.710 --> 00:27:47.940 position:56%
And the radio is blaring and there's
a [inaudible] and it's burning hot.

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:49.530
And you're watching them.

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:51.890
And they're sweating.

00:27:51.890 --> 00:27:53.190
And even as a little kid,

00:27:53.190 --> 00:27:57.640
you realize that their flavor
is going into the food.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:27:59.140
Right? They're making this thing.

00:27:59.140 --> 00:28:01.450
Their sweat is falling into it.

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:08.920
And I even at seven, eight, was
having a super erotic moment

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:16.050
because I was looking up
at them thinking, "Oh, oh,

00:28:16.050 --> 00:28:17.770
you dusky princesses [laughter]."

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:27.210
Right? I was like, "I
shall marry all six of you.

00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:31.240
Just wait for me though.

00:28:31.240 --> 00:28:33.050
I got to catch up, but I'm coming."

00:28:33.050 --> 00:28:39.520
And they were so sweet because,
you know, the older women

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:44.310
in our cultures have so
many codes of generosity

00:28:44.310 --> 00:28:45.930
and kindness and strength.

00:28:45.930 --> 00:28:47.530
Not just [foreign language spoken].

00:28:47.530 --> 00:28:49.510
And they would look at me
and they would go nuts.

00:28:49.510 --> 00:28:54.100
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:28:54.100 --> 00:28:56.230
The little blonde boy
[foreign language spoken].

00:28:56.230 --> 00:29:00.110
I was like, "Yeah.

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:03.290
I am hot. Yes."

00:29:03.290 --> 00:29:04.590
And they'd be like,
"[foreign language spoken]."

00:29:04.590 --> 00:29:09.500
And I'd be like, "Dang
right I want a tortilla."

00:29:09.500 --> 00:29:11.070
And I'd say, "Si.

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:12.370
Por favor."

00:29:12.370 --> 00:29:14.030
And they would take a hot tortilla.

00:29:14.030 --> 00:29:17.730
And they'd put a little salt in
it, roll it up, and give it to me.

00:29:17.730 --> 00:29:21.830
Come on. And then on a really
good day they had butter.

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:24.040
And they'd put butter on it
and roll it up and give it,

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:26.870
I was just like, mm-hmm, yeah.

00:29:26.870 --> 00:29:30.320
And then they would
give me that hot kilo.

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:35.050
And I would carry it back
warming my body to feed my family.

00:29:35.050 --> 00:29:38.270
Holy cow. How powerful is that?

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:40.010
And I carry them with me.

00:29:40.010 --> 00:29:41.510
I carry them with me.

00:29:41.510 --> 00:29:43.940
And the women that I
saw when I was a kid.

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:47.620
My upbringing was absent
men pretty much.

00:29:47.620 --> 00:29:50.830
My dad was out and
about being a man.

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:53.690
And he'd come home and
check on me and make sure,

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:56.210
want to see if I was being
a man or not [laughter].

00:29:56.210 --> 00:30:00.670
And he was never happy with
how much of a man I was.

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:07.830
But to watch the miracle
I think of the daily life.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:11.400
I became kind of obsessed
with capturing the daily life.

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:14.330
Watching my godmother garden.

00:30:14.330 --> 00:30:20.140
Watching her daughters
sort the pinto beans.

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:25.980
This act that was so graceful
and so invisible, nobody thought

00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:28.320
about it or saw it except me.

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:32.760
I would sit all morning and watch
and how they would put the beans

00:30:32.760 --> 00:30:38.210
on the table and start sifting them
around and raking the good beans

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:41.550
into a pot they held between their
knees and without even looking,

00:30:41.550 --> 00:30:46.220
flick away little pebbles and
sticks without seeing them.

00:30:46.220 --> 00:30:48.750
But they knew they were
there until they had the pot.

00:30:48.750 --> 00:30:51.010
And then they could
make food to feed us.

00:30:51.010 --> 00:30:55.030
And how I would try to
tell them my newest poems.

00:30:55.030 --> 00:30:56.470
And they would say,
"[foreign language spoken].

00:30:56.470 --> 00:30:59.710
You talk so pretty."

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:04.860
Wow, man. Writing, right?

00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:09.870
Later on we moved up to a little
white, working class suburb.

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:12.890
I was telling people earlier today,

00:31:12.890 --> 00:31:16.750
I had never seen lawns
until the fifth grade.

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:19.580
I saw grass.

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:23.530 position:56%
And I remember thinking, "Wow, these
white dudes are billionaires, man.

00:31:23.530 --> 00:31:27.670
They pour water on their
yards and they have grass."

00:31:27.670 --> 00:31:30.840
And I also ate sliced bread.

00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:36.440
I grew up eating peanut butter
sandwiches on corn tortillas.

00:31:36.440 --> 00:31:39.860
We called it "la peanut butter."

00:31:39.860 --> 00:31:42.620
There I was in this new
world and I have to tell you

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:46.160
that this big transformation
happened in the fifth grade.

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:49.250
I did all this new stuff.

00:31:49.250 --> 00:31:55.280
I had a very strong Tijuana accent
until I moved to that neighborhood.

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:56.930
I have relatives still
talk like this.

00:31:56.930 --> 00:31:59.940
OK? If I go to Mexico very
long, I come back like,

00:31:59.940 --> 00:32:01.620
my friends think I'm kidding.

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:03.830
They're like, "What is this man?"

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:08.240
"What? [inaudible]."

00:32:08.240 --> 00:32:13.450
But we got up there and it
started changing immediately.

00:32:13.450 --> 00:32:15.910
And I know exactly when it changed.

00:32:15.910 --> 00:32:18.090
They didn't know what my name was.

00:32:18.090 --> 00:32:23.440
Right? So, I was, of course,
urine, diarrhea, urethra.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:25.770
They didn't know what
the heck it was.

00:32:25.770 --> 00:32:29.880
They started calling me unreal,
which I thought was awesome.

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:32.090
For a guy that wanted
to be a famous author

00:32:32.090 --> 00:32:35.010
or be in Led Zeppelin,
it didn't matter.

00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:37.590
Unreal. Cool name.

00:32:37.590 --> 00:32:42.270
So, I joined the Boy Scouts.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:45.830
And the Boy Scouts were
heaven for a kid like me.

00:32:45.830 --> 00:32:47.340
Going camping and stuff.

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:51.040
And my old man did not approve.

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:52.340
He didn't like it.

00:32:52.340 --> 00:32:55.920
He'd be like, "Meijo,
[inaudible] Boy Scouts.

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:58.560
You wore green shorts, meijo."

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:01.930
I was like, "Yeah, Dad."

00:33:01.930 --> 00:33:04.150
"You wear green shorts
and long socks

00:33:04.150 --> 00:33:06.660
and you wear a handkerchief
on your neck."

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:09.000
I said, "Yeah, it's my
neckerchief [phonetic].

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.030
It's got a slide and everything."

00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:14.850
And my dad said, "If you want to be
a man, join the Army [inaudible]."

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:17.810
And I was like, "Dad,
I'm in fifth grade."

00:33:17.810 --> 00:33:21.850
It was always about
being a man, you know?

00:33:21.850 --> 00:33:24.600
But here is where the change came.

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:26.790
And I think about this a lot.

00:33:26.790 --> 00:33:30.190
Almost every time I turn
on the TV right now.

00:33:30.190 --> 00:33:35.360
I was with my boys, my new
homies, and we had been camping

00:33:35.360 --> 00:33:36.660
and doing all this stuff.

00:33:36.660 --> 00:33:37.960
The Bat Patrol.

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:39.260
Troop 260.

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:40.560
Bat Patrol.

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:42.090
And we were in the bathroom.

00:33:42.090 --> 00:33:43.580
Fifth grade.

00:33:43.580 --> 00:33:46.130
About to head into sixth grade.

00:33:46.130 --> 00:33:49.170
And everybody is in there
doing their business.

00:33:49.170 --> 00:33:52.740
And there was this one kid,
bright red hair, freckles.

00:33:52.740 --> 00:33:56.500
I mean the classic suburban
white boy, you know?

00:33:56.500 --> 00:33:57.800
And they're all my buds.

00:33:57.800 --> 00:34:01.690
And he turns to me and
he says, "Hey, Unreal."

00:34:01.690 --> 00:34:02.990
And I said, "Yeah."

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:05.230
And he said, "You know
what you are, man?"

00:34:05.230 --> 00:34:06.840
I said, "No, what am I?"

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:09.230
He said, "You're a greaser."

00:34:09.230 --> 00:34:11.840
And they all turned to
me and started laughing.

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:13.140
And I said, "I'm a what?"

00:34:13.140 --> 00:34:16.480
He said, "You're a
greaser, wet back."

00:34:16.480 --> 00:34:19.520
And all my homies started
in, "Greaser wet back.

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:20.820
Greaser wet back."

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:22.330
And they all walked out together.

00:34:22.330 --> 00:34:23.630
And I was standing there.

00:34:23.630 --> 00:34:25.210
And, you know, you're a kid.

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:27.020
You internalize it, right?

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:29.700
And you think, "Greaser wet back."

00:34:29.700 --> 00:34:37.860
I thought, nobody told us
that we're wet with grease

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:44.300
that only these folks in the
north part of the city can see it.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:47.540
And I remember taking
off my shirt and trying

00:34:47.540 --> 00:34:50.100 position:56%
to find the grease on my undershirt.

00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:54.030
That was a shock.

00:34:54.030 --> 00:35:00.240
And my cousins would come up from
Mexico and they couldn't figure

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:03.670
out the whole dynamic
of race and so forth

00:35:03.670 --> 00:35:06.110
because they weren't
poor kids like me.

00:35:06.110 --> 00:35:08.950
They were actually kind
of royalty down there.

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:13.160
And in Southern California they
had all kinds of names for us

00:35:13.160 --> 00:35:14.970
but the one that was
kind of creative,

00:35:14.970 --> 00:35:16.560
they could call us taco benders

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:19.630
because there is a nice little
u-shape in the taco, right?

00:35:19.630 --> 00:35:21.350
It's pretty creative.

00:35:21.350 --> 00:35:24.120
And I was walking down the
street with my cousin Jamie

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:26.210
who didn't speak English.

00:35:26.210 --> 00:35:27.670
He was a Beatles fiend.

00:35:27.670 --> 00:35:32.670
He knew English from
phonetic recounting

00:35:32.670 --> 00:35:34.320
of Beatles songs [inaudible].

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:42.020
And he would sing,
you know [inaudible].

00:35:42.020 --> 00:35:45.490
You know? Old [inaudible].

00:35:45.490 --> 00:35:49.810
So, we're walking down the street
and a guy in a truck pulled up

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:52.870
and yelled, "Hey, taco bender."

00:35:52.870 --> 00:36:01.550
And he said, "What you want
cheeseburger [laughter]?"

00:36:01.550 --> 00:36:04.750
His one English lesson.

00:36:04.750 --> 00:36:06.980
So, words meant so much to me.

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:08.770
They always meant so much to me.

00:36:08.770 --> 00:36:12.280
And the thing I want to leave
with you before I go to questions

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:16.400
or comments if you have
any, is that at that moment

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:22.550
when I suddenly internalized
shame, I was so shocked.

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:24.960
All of the sudden people
didn't like Mexicans.

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:27.090
I thought everybody loved us.

00:36:27.090 --> 00:36:29.910
I thought Tia Flaca was awesome.

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:32.500
I thought my grandma was cool.

00:36:32.500 --> 00:36:35.360
I thought Rampa Independencia
was cool.

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:41.160
I thought Ugo Milan was super cool
and all of the sudden we weren't.

00:36:41.160 --> 00:36:46.330
And that was a great
and tremendous shock.

00:36:46.330 --> 00:36:50.880
So, everything I held
sacred was suddenly trash

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:52.790
in the culture in which I was in.

00:36:52.790 --> 00:36:56.530
And it took me a long time to
figure out how to deal with that.

00:36:56.530 --> 00:36:58.140
Thank god for words.

00:36:58.140 --> 00:37:01.090
When I got to college,
Southern California

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:03.570
in those days was not a
place to expect to learn

00:37:03.570 --> 00:37:09.560
that there were Latino writers or
women writers or black writers.

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:13.160
I get to college and
they're like, "OK.

00:37:13.160 --> 00:37:20.590
We're going to be reading
[inaudible], Carlos Fuentes."

00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:22.750
I said, "Who?

00:37:22.750 --> 00:37:25.700
What?" What a miracle.

00:37:25.700 --> 00:37:30.990
So, I felt like I got kind of
atomized and then reintegrated.

00:37:30.990 --> 00:37:32.700
And something, it was good.

00:37:32.700 --> 00:37:35.460
It was like a transporter beam
in Star Trek or something.

00:37:35.460 --> 00:37:38.730
I felt like my cells
were purified in a way.

00:37:38.730 --> 00:37:43.360
And so I decided what I had
to do was do a literature

00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:45.600
of witness for the rest of my life.

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:47.380
I was a poor boy like I told you.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:49.310
I wanted to be Stephen King.

00:37:49.310 --> 00:37:52.750
I wanted to be Robert
Plant or Steve McQueen.

00:37:52.750 --> 00:37:55.850
I just wanted a bunch
of cars and a plane.

00:37:55.850 --> 00:37:58.630
And for a long time I
thought if I wrote love poems

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:00.970
to my girlfriend Collette,
that would happen.

00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:05.220
Wrong. But I realized
that I wanted to witness.

00:38:05.220 --> 00:38:06.780
And that meant witness everybody.

00:38:06.780 --> 00:38:11.020
And sometimes it means having
to put your prejudice aside,

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:13.610
because I'm loaded with it,
class rage and prejudice,

00:38:13.610 --> 00:38:17.420
and try to see everybody
that you're writing about

00:38:17.420 --> 00:38:20.360
and give them a fair reading.

00:38:20.360 --> 00:38:21.660
And that can be really hard,

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:25.100
but that has been my
obsession ever since.

00:38:25.100 --> 00:38:27.650
So, that's a little bit
of where I came from.

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:32.270
That and about 300 notebooks
full of really bad writing.

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:33.870
And here we are now.

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:35.520
So, thanks for listening.

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:38.510
And if you have any
questions [inaudible].

00:38:38.510 --> 00:38:46.340
